 not happen easily. Legislative battles raged over the propriety of discriminating by race or of smoothing away the effects of capitalism's fluctuations on individuals. Meanwhile, debates within companies set doctors against actuaries and agents, resulting in elaborate, secretive systems of surveillance and calculation. Dan Bouk reveals how, in a little over half a century, insurers laid the groundwork for the much-quantified, risk-infused world that we live in today. To understand how the financial world shapes modern bodies, how risk assessments can perpetuate inequalities of race or sex, and how the quantification and claims of risk on each of us continue to grow, we must take seriously the history of those who view our lives as a series of probabilities to be managed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aInsurance companiesxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aInsurancexStatistical methodsxHistory. 0aLife insurancezUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  astatistics, statistical, data, quantitative, qualitative, capitalism, american, america, history, historical, united states, usa, numerical, math, mathematic, life insurance, risk, assessment, science, scientific, corporate, culture, cultural, corporations, business, intellectual, professional, workplace, everyday, legal, legislation, discrimination, racism, equity, contemporary, modern world, inequality, equality, social studies, society.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022625917840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226259208423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226259208/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles